flowRoot.flowPara: The first step is to assemble and practice the use of your Foldscope. All the components and instructions are included and can be popped out of the cardboard net. Give yourselves some time to experiment with this!

Next follow our guide to making simple PDMS silicon moulds from fragments of vinyl records and surplus electronics provided. The foldscope is an elegant deceptively simple microscope, combining a ball lens like the first microscopes of Antonie van Leeuwenhoek with contemporary engineering testing practices and mass manufacturing. It's meant to help 'anyone' experience the microbiological world in a hands on way. You'll get quite intimate with your Foldscope equipment to get it to 'work' and be able to 'see' with it.
Make tiny environments with us & you get to intervene in the microbiological world. This is a key activity in 'doing' science or art.

Using everyday objects of our techno-scientific world, makes us think how much humans intervene in the world at all scales. What other objects in your worlds can you find that might make tiny spaces we can use? Go find some & take part in our research and tell us about it!

Prepared & labelled syringes filled with PDMS (A) & hardener (B). PDMS is a non-volatile silicon and safe to handle, but not ingest. We advise taking care to wash your hands thoroughly after use and store them in the already open plastic sleeves. Unmixed they store for up to a year. Be careful not to cross contaminate the A & B components or they will harden in storage.
555 Timer chip. Common chip in maker projects and many electronic devices.
Micro-petri-dish with lid. Mix PDMS together and make impressions with chip surfaces. You could use anything you think might make tiny impressions in the surface of your PDMS mould.
Place your chip & logo or vinyl groove fragment down into the mix, pressing gently into the bottom of the dish. Cover and leave to set for
You can use any other object that you thing might work here, PDMS can get in the tiniest spaces

Carefully remove from the mix then with a sharp knife (not included for safety) and tweezers (included) cut & remove the recessed impression of the chip/vinyl and carefully place on your microscope slide, impression, 'bumpy', groove side down.

Insert the glass slide into the Foldscope a few times to make it easier to insert your slide later: the card slots are very tight on first use. Use your pipette to inject a drop of algae suspension from your Eppendorf tube into the side of the impressed silicon. Capilliary action should pull the liquid into the tiny impressions of the chip surface markings or the vinyl channels.
You can also place a cover slip over your slab of silicon, especially if it breaks into pieces (which happens alot!)
Insert your prepared slide here & be careful slotting it in, not to push your coverslip away or cut yourself on it, it's breakable and sharp if broken)

Vinyl fragment. Some of you may not remember, but at the dawn of pop culture and capitalism music was distributed widely on vinyl discs as micrometre scale grooves that could be amplified and played back
